A team is deploying a cross-namespace Nexus service in Temporal Cloud. Their handler Workflow occasionally takes 8 minutes to complete. The caller Workflow sets only a `ScheduleToCloseTimeout` of 10 minutes on the Nexus Operation. During a load spike, the handler Worker becomes temporarily unavailable for 3 minutes after the Operation starts, then recovers. Which statement best describes what happens to the caller Workflow during this period?

Caller code:
```csharp
var output = await Workflow.CreateNexusWorkflowClient<IHelloService>(IHelloService.EndpointName)
    .ExecuteNexusOperationAsync(svc => svc.SayHello(new(name, language)), new NexusWorkflowOperationOptions
    {
        ScheduleToCloseTimeout = TimeSpan.FromMinutes(10),
    });
```

A developer writes a caller Workflow that cancels a long-running asynchronous Nexus Operation. They use the default cancellation type. The handler Workflow receives the cancellation request but decides to ignore it and runs to normal completion. The caller Workflow has already received acknowledgment that cancellation was requested. What is the actual outcome for the caller Workflow?

Caller code:
```csharp
[WorkflowRun]
public async Task<string> RunAsync(string name, IHelloService.HelloLanguage language)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
    var opTask = Workflow.CreateNexusWorkflowClient<IHelloService>(IHelloService.EndpointName)
        .ExecuteNexusOperationAsync(svc => svc.SayHello(new(name, language)),
            cancellationToken: cts.Token);
    // ... some time later
    cts.Cancel();
    return await opTask;
}
```
